         <div type="entry">
                <head>Giwargis of Bʿeltan</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Giwargis-of-Beltan</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/239</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">230</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="178-179"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/139</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">
                        <abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>
                        <abbr> 
                     <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> (758-89).<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(<abbr>Patr.</abbr> 758–789) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>
                        <abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>
                        <abbr> 
                     <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> (758–89). Giwargis was born in Bʿeltan, near <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Hims">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/215">Ḥimṣ</placeName>
                        </ref>
                        (Emesa), perhaps in a <abbr>Melk.</abbr> family (according to a non-Syriac source [see
                        Evetts, 413]), but apparently at a young age he turned <abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr> He was
                        educated in Syriac and Greek learning in the <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Qenneshre-Monastery-of">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/230">Monastery
                            of Qenneshre</placeName>
                        </ref>.</p>
                    <p>After the death of <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Athanasios IV <choice>
                            <sic>Sandaloyo</sic>
                            <corr>Sandloyo</corr>
                        </choice>, at the electoral synod at
                        Mabbug in December 758, though still only a deacon, he was chosen <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr>
                        Mesopotamian bishops opposed his elevation and somewhat later chose Yuḥanon
                        of the <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Qarqaphto-Monastery-of">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/229">Monastery
                            of Qarqaphto</placeName>
                        </ref>, <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Kallinikos/Raqqaʿ, as an anti-patriarch. The
                        schism could have ended in 762, when Yuḥanon of Kallinikos died, but at the
                        synod at Serugh in 764/5 the Mesopotamian bishops accepted Dawid <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Dara
                        as the successor to the deceased anti-patriarch.</p>
                    <p>Dawid accused Giwargis of tax irregularities, and Caliph Abū Jaʿfar ʿAbdullāh
                        al-Manṣūr (754–75) put him in prison for nine years (767–75). After this
                        Caliph’s death his son and successor, al-Mahdī, upon his accession in 775
                        released Giwargis, on the condition that he was not to exercise his office
                        or title. Eventually, in 777, he was confirmed in his office by the Muslim
                        authorities.</p>
                    <p>On 22 May 785 he presided over the synod in Kfar-Nabu in the region of Serugh
                        at which 22 canons, mostly of a disciplinary nature, were passed.</p>
                    <p>During one of his pastoral journeys, in the region of Qlaudia, he fell sick
                        and not long thereafter he died in the year 789/790 in <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Barsawmo-Dayro-d-Mor">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/224">Dayro d-Mor
                            Barṣawmo</placeName>
                        </ref> near <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Melitene">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/136">Melitene</placeName>
                        </ref>, where he
                        was also buried.</p>
                    <p>During his imprisonment he is reported to have written numerous discourses
                        and metrical homilies (<hi rend="italic">memre</hi>), not preserved, as well
                        as an exegetical work, the ‘Commentary on the Gospel of Matthew’, which
                        displays his knowledge of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/John-Chrysostom">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/573">John
                            Chrysostom</persName>
                        </ref>, the Cappadocian fathers, and <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Philoxenos-of-Mabbug">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/44">Philoxenos
                            of Mabbug</persName>
                        </ref> (<abbr>ms.</abbr> Vat. Syr. 154, not published). He wrote also
                        synodal letters and a letter to a deacon Guria of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Edessa">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName>
                        </ref> (quoted by
                            <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Michael-I-Rabo">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/217">Michael Rabo</persName>
                        </ref>, Chronicle, vol. 3, 5–8) on the
                        formula ‘We break the heavenly bread’, the use of which later became the
                        subject of a long controversy.</p>
                </div>
